    "summary": "Nineveh, located on the east bank of the Tigris River in present-day northern Iraq near modern Mosul, was one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities of the ancient Near East, with occupation dating back to at least 6000 BCE. During the [[event:1617|Uruk period]] (4000–3000 BCE), Nineveh was an established settlement associated with the worship of Ishtar (Inanna), the goddess of love and war, whose temple at Nineveh was already ancient by historical times. Nineveh Ware, a distinctive painted pottery style from the early third millennium BCE, is named after the site.\n\nIn its early phases, Nineveh was a regional religious and trade center rather than a major political capital. Its strategic position on the Tigris, at the intersection of routes linking Mesopotamia with Anatolia, the Zagros mountains, and the Iranian Plateau, gave it enduring commercial importance. The city would eventually become the capital of the Neo-Assyrian Empire in the first millennium BCE, when it was one of the largest cities in the ancient world under kings such as Sennacherib and Ashurbanipal. The deep prehistoric roots of Nineveh illustrate the remarkable continuity of occupation at favored Mesopotamian sites.",
